00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:26.130
then everybody will get either a PCV 20 or 15 slash 23.

639
00:26:26.130 --> 00:26:27.330
Although that's gonna go away too

640
00:26:27.330 --> 00:26:28.890
'cause we'll just have the 20.

641
00:26:28.890 --> 00:26:31.860
And the biggest piece is you only get it once in life.

642
00:26:31.860 --> 00:26:34.290
There's no more of this, you get another one at 65.

643
00:26:34.290 --> 00:26:37.290
I will say 90% of the time when I go to the app,

644
00:26:37.290 --> 00:26:39.540
it will tell me that the patient is fully immunized.

645
00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:41.460
If they want to get a 20, they can get one.

646
00:26:41.460 --> 00:26:44.790
But regardless they will be considered fully immunized.

647
00:26:44.790 --> 00:26:46.230
But that's all I would worry about

648
00:26:46.230 --> 00:26:48.491
with this is a one PCV 20.

649
00:26:48.491 --> 00:26:50.037
Okay, Dr. Fernhaber.

650
00:26:50.037 --> 00:26:51.900
<v ->Two kind of major categories of question.</v>

651
00:26:51.900 --> 00:26:54.510
One was bare metal versus drug-eluting stent,

652
00:26:54.510 --> 00:26:56.520
when would I choose one over the other?

653
00:26:56.520 --> 00:26:58.530
Well the easy answer there is you won't,

654
00:26:58.530 --> 00:26:59.733
it's not your choice.

655
00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:03.480
But the broader answer is bare metal stents are

656
00:27:03.480 --> 00:27:06.150
typically used in larger lesions.

657
00:27:06.150 --> 00:27:09.480
There is some, and it's gonna sound kind of cynical,

658
00:27:09.480 --> 00:27:12.720
but there is some assessment of patient ability,

659
00:27:12.720 --> 00:27:15.210
whether that is ability to follow instructions

660
00:27:15.210 --> 00:27:18.360
or ability to pay for dual antiplatelet therapy,

661
00:27:18.360 --> 00:27:20.880
which is really critical with a drug-eluting stent

662
00:27:20.880 --> 00:27:23.010
because the risk of stent thrombosis

663
00:27:23.010 --> 00:27:25.410
with a drug-eluting stent is substantial for up

664
00:27:25.410 --> 00:27:26.790
to 12 plus months.

665
00:27:26.790 --> 00:27:29.010
And if someone has demonstrated number one

666
00:27:29.010 --> 00:27:31.240
that they're not willing to or not able to

667
00:27:32.100 --> 00:27:35.130
adhere to dual antiplatelet therapy,

668
00:27:35.130 --> 00:27:36.720
they are not necessarily a good candidate

669
00:27:36.720 --> 00:27:39.780
for a drug-eluting stent, a bare metal stent may be better.

670
00:27:39.780 --> 00:27:43.260
Drug-eluting stents typically used in smaller, more secure,

671
00:27:43.260 --> 00:27:47.760
more difficult lesions and in lesions that are bifurcating

672
00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:49.427
or lesions that occur at bifurcations.

673
00:27:49.427 --> 00:27:51.750
'Cause you can, if you are happen

674
00:27:51.750 --> 00:27:52.860
to be an invasive cardiologist,

675
00:27:52.860 --> 00:27:55.890
you can put a drug-eluting stent typically deployed into a

676
00:27:55.890 --> 00:27:58.853
smaller lesion where the risk of in-stent stenosis

677
00:27:58.853 --> 00:28:01.080
is a bit more critical.

678
00:28:01.080 --> 00:28:02.880
Other question and a big clump

679
00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:05.670
of questions about the cardiovascular outcomes data

680
00:28:05.670 --> 00:28:08.040
with ezetimibe, it is really limited.

681
00:28:08.040 --> 00:28:11.760
So the enhanced IT trial was, gosh,

682
00:28:11.760 --> 00:28:13.350
it came out probably 15 years ago.

683
00:28:13.350 --> 00:28:15.990
It was simvastatin plus ezetimibe

684
00:28:15.990 --> 00:28:19.530
and seven years of data in like 25,000 patients.

685
00:28:19.530 --> 00:28:20.610
Which always makes me nervous

686
00:28:20.610 --> 00:28:23.820
that it took 25,000 patients to get outcomes.

687
00:28:23.820 --> 00:28:27.000
But finally after seven years they released data saying the

688
00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:31.200
combination is of the ezetimibe plus simvastatin was better

689
00:28:31.200 --> 00:28:34.230
than either one alone, better than simvastatin alone.

690
00:28:34.230 --> 00:28:37.650
So there is outcomes data, it's not spectacular,

691
00:28:37.650 --> 00:28:39.870
it is the use of ezetimibe now

692
00:28:39.870 --> 00:28:41.760
is largely extrapolated from that.

693
00:28:41.760 --> 00:28:44.310
But it's also because we don't have other good drugs right

694
00:28:44.310 --> 00:28:48.180
now that effectively lower LDL in conjunction

695
00:28:48.180 --> 00:28:52.260
with the statin and have at least some bit of outcomes data.

696
00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:54.210
So that's kind of the best that we have.

697
00:28:54.210 --> 00:28:55.920
Back when ezetimibe was super expensive,

698
00:28:55.920 --> 00:28:59.460
when it was branded, it was really not a well favored drug.

699
00:28:59.460 --> 00:29:01.500
Now that it's moved to generic status

700
00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:05.250
and it's relatively inexpensive, the cost-benefit ratio

701
00:29:05.250 --> 00:29:08.400
or cost-benefit analysis, there definitely leans in favor

702
00:29:08.400 --> 00:29:11.100
of using ezetimibe a little bit more liberally.

703
00:29:11.100 --> 00:29:12.360
<v ->I'm gonna just answer one here</v>

704
00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:15.330
'cause there seems to be a lot of hubbub about that.

705
00:29:15.330 --> 00:29:17.400
The point I wanna make with question one related

706
00:29:17.400 --> 00:29:21.600
to hypertension is that you do not have to have proteinuria

707
00:29:21.600 --> 00:29:24.330
to make the diagnosis of preeclampsia, okay?

708
00:29:24.330 --> 00:29:26.970
<v ->And that's really important here</v>

709
00:29:26.970 --> 00:29:29.760
as we look at risk here, okay?

710
00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:33.630
So if there's any question on the exam

711
00:29:33.630 --> 00:29:35.940
where they tell you the blood pressure is elevated,

712
00:29:35.940 --> 00:29:39.270
but there's no proteinuria, don't be making the assumption

713
00:29:39.270 --> 00:29:41.070
that it can't be preeclampsia.

714
00:29:41.070 --> 00:29:43.980
You're gonna look in that patient specific question

715
00:29:43.980 --> 00:29:45.510
at other risk factors

716
00:29:45.510 --> 00:29:49.020
associated with severe preeclampsia, which is going

717
00:29:49.020 --> 00:29:53.400
to give you the diagnosis as well as if the same

718
00:29:53.400 --> 00:29:55.470
as if I had proteinuria, okay?

719
00:29:55.470 --> 00:29:57.900
So that's the focus I want to make with

720
00:29:57.900 --> 00:30:00.870
that particular question here, okay?

721
00:30:00.870 --> 00:30:02.430
This is a new question this time

722
00:30:02.430 --> 00:30:05.520
and clearly it's going to take some further refinement,

723
00:30:05.520 --> 00:30:08.910
but the goal here is proteinuria does not define

724
00:30:08.910 --> 00:30:10.380
preeclampsia any longer.

725
00:30:10.380 --> 00:30:13.260
Just like, in the way olden days,

726
00:30:13.260 --> 00:30:17.010
the triad that some of you recall is you had to have a edema

727
00:30:17.010 --> 00:30:19.530
and that was removed over a decade ago

728
00:30:19.530 --> 00:30:21.780
because kind of like back pain, it's hard

729
00:30:21.780 --> 00:30:25.470
to find a pregnant woman without edema.

730
00:30:25.470 --> 00:30:27.150
That's why you, it's almost impossible

731
00:30:27.150 --> 00:30:29.220
to find a pregnant woman without back pain.

732
00:30:29.220 --> 00:30:31.860
You're moving her center of gravity forward and

733
00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:33.660
therefore her back is compensating

734
00:30:33.660 --> 00:30:35.790
to keep her from falling on her face.

735
00:30:35.790 --> 00:30:38.643
And there's always going to be pain associated with it.

736
00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:42.960
Please join me in thanking all of our presenters.

737
00:30:42.960 --> 00:30:46.410
<v ->All right, I've got three quick ones here.</v>

738
00:30:46.410 --> 00:30:48.450
One is, if you have patients who are previously treated

739
00:30:48.450 --> 00:30:50.760
with beta blocker monotherapy for hypertension, do you need

740
00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:53.730
to switch them to a more appropriate first line option?

741
00:30:53.730 --> 00:30:56.010
And I think you could take that same question

742
00:30:56.010 --> 00:30:59.850
and insert almost any drug that isn't in the big four

743
00:30:59.850 --> 00:31:02.430
and say if someone is well controlled,

744
00:31:02.430 --> 00:31:04.020
do you necessarily make changes?

745
00:31:04.020 --> 00:31:06.480
And the answer is no, not necessarily.

746
00:31:06.480 --> 00:31:09.840
Likewise, I won't change someone from HCTZ if

747
00:31:09.840 --> 00:31:11.490
they're doing fine.

748
00:31:11.490 --> 00:31:13.710
However, if you see someone for example,

749
00:31:13.710 --> 00:31:16.920
who may be on beta block or alpha block or monotherapy

750
00:31:16.920 --> 00:31:19.440
and you see them for hypertension,

751
00:31:19.440 --> 00:31:21.420
even if their blood pressure looks okay,

752
00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:22.920
many times you're gonna find some other

753
00:31:22.920 --> 00:31:25.740
compelling comorbidity that would prompt you to switch them

754
00:31:25.740 --> 00:31:27.600
to another class of drugs.

755
00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:30.120
They have diabetes, they now have something else

756
00:31:30.120 --> 00:31:32.010
that might adjust your therapy.

757
00:31:32.010 --> 00:31:33.510
So I have no problems making changes.

758
00:31:33.510 --> 00:31:36.540
One, when I see a new patient, one of my first questions is,

759
00:31:36.540 --> 00:31:38.700
how much of this can I change?

760
00:31:38.700 --> 00:31:41.520
And if the answer is I'm really happy with everything,

761
00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:42.660
then I kind of take a step back.

762
00:31:42.660 --> 00:31:46.380
If they're like we're not liking anything, then we go to it.

763
00:31:46.380 --> 00:31:47.213
Let's see here.

764
00:31:47.213 --> 00:31:48.660
Can you use ACE inhibitors in patients

765
00:31:48.660 --> 00:31:51.000
with history of chronic urticaria?

766
00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:54.060
Yes, the one contraindication for ACE inhibitor

767
00:31:54.060 --> 00:31:56.520
is if someone has a history of anaphylaxis,

768
00:31:56.520 --> 00:31:59.490
even if that anaphylaxis is not drug related.

769
00:31:59.490 --> 00:32:01.500
For example, if they have a bee sting allergy,

770
00:32:01.500 --> 00:32:04.770
an anaphylaxis sometime in the past required epinephrine

771
00:32:04.770 --> 00:32:06.960
from a bee sting that would preclude the

772
00:32:06.960 --> 00:32:07.980
use of ACE inhibitors.

773
00:32:07.980 --> 00:32:09.080
You should use an ARB.

774
00:32:10.680 --> 00:32:13.533
Final one, and this I think is really a,

775
00:32:14.700 --> 00:32:15.720
I don't know if it was intended

776
00:32:15.720 --> 00:32:18.150
to be a super good question, but I think it is.

777
00:32:18.150 --> 00:32:19.740
If a patient comes in with hypertension

778
00:32:19.740 --> 00:32:21.930
and tachycardia, would you want to start

779
00:32:21.930 --> 00:32:24.333
with diltiazem since it will lower both?

780
00:32:25.170 --> 00:32:26.610
Technically the answer is yes.

781
00:32:26.610 --> 00:32:29.820
Diltiazem can lower heart rate as can a beta blocker

782
00:32:29.820 --> 00:32:31.413
and can lower blood pressure.

783
00:32:32.370 --> 00:32:34.290
I skipped a couple beats when I read this question

784
00:32:34.290 --> 00:32:37.650
because sinus tachycardias I'll talk about tomorrow

785
00:32:37.650 --> 00:32:38.730
is a secondary rhythm.

786
00:32:38.730 --> 00:32:41.160
Sinus tachycardia is due to something.

787
00:32:41.160 --> 00:32:43.710
We don't reflexively treat tachycardia just

788
00:32:43.710 --> 00:32:45.030
because heart rate is up.

789
00:32:45.030 --> 00:32:46.590
We look to see what is the reason

790
00:32:46.590 --> 00:32:48.210
for the heart rate elevation.

791
00:32:48.210 --> 00:32:50.610
The worst thing that I can imagine is someone who has,

792
00:32:50.610 --> 00:32:53.730
for example, heart failure with preserved ejection fraction.

793
00:32:53.730 --> 00:32:55.050
They have a low stroke volume

794
00:32:55.050 --> 00:32:57.210
because they have diastolic dysfunction.

795
00:32:57.210 --> 00:32:59.100
If you recall, cardiac output is a function

796
00:32:59.100 --> 00:33:00.720
of heart rate and stroke volume.

797
00:33:00.720 --> 00:33:01.890
Their tachycardia may be

798
00:33:01.890 --> 00:33:04.770
what is keeping their cardiac output alive.

799
00:33:04.770 --> 00:33:07.140
So just reflexively saying heart rate is up,

800
00:33:07.140 --> 00:33:10.290
I turn down heart rate may cause decompensation

801
00:33:10.290 --> 00:33:11.940
of heart failure at the worst.

802
00:33:11.940 --> 00:33:13.110
Do they have atrial fibrillation?

803
00:33:13.110 --> 00:33:13.943
Do they have flutter?

804
00:33:13.943 --> 00:33:15.150
Do they have a lot of PVCs?

805
00:33:15.150 --> 00:33:16.500
Do they have something else

806
00:33:16.500 --> 00:33:18.300
that is making their heart rate elevated?

807
00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:22.710
So the answer is find out what is causing the tachycardia.

808
00:33:22.710 --> 00:33:24.420
If you do wanna dial down heart rate,

809
00:33:24.420 --> 00:33:26.880
a non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker probably

810
00:33:26.880 --> 00:33:28.020
isn't your first choice.

811
00:33:28.020 --> 00:33:29.940
They do slow AV conduction

812
00:33:29.940 --> 00:33:31.890
but they don't directly affect the assay node.

813
00:33:31.890 --> 00:33:34.590
Whereas beta blockers will slow heart rate more

814
00:33:34.590 --> 00:33:37.543
directly and I'll stop.

815
00:33:37.543 --> 00:33:38.376
<v ->Gonna do the top three.</v>

816
00:33:38.376 --> 00:33:40.680
The others are all what we call what I call one off,

817
00:33:40.680 --> 00:33:41.880
meaning just one person.

818
00:33:41.880 --> 00:33:43.440
So I will answer those online.

819
00:33:43.440 --> 00:33:46.530
Number one, can you write an EPT script for trick as well?

820
00:33:46.530 --> 00:33:47.730
Yes.

821
00:33:47.730 --> 00:33:50.790
Is an annual pelvic exam needed routinely at any age?

822
00:33:50.790 --> 00:33:51.900
No.

823
00:33:51.900 --> 00:33:53.760
Are you able to write EPT prescription

824
00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:58.170
with refills if the patient suspects more than one partner.

825
00:33:58.170 --> 00:34:00.120
You wouldn't be writing it with refills.

826
00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:02.850
You would be writing the number of prescriptions

827
00:34:02.850 --> 00:34:04.560
that the patient needs.

828
00:34:04.560 --> 00:34:07.380
You know, if in the last 60 days they say listen,

829
00:34:07.380 --> 00:34:10.440
I have been with five other partners

830
00:34:10.440 --> 00:34:13.800
and I know who they are, then you would write

831
00:34:13.800 --> 00:34:14.970
and I know who they are

832
00:34:14.970 --> 00:34:16.530
but I don't know their names,

833
00:34:16.530 --> 00:34:19.980
then you would write five EPT prescriptions

834
00:34:19.980 --> 00:34:23.310
and he or she would give those to the individual

835
00:34:23.310 --> 00:34:27.150
or they would be called into the pharmacy.

836
00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:30.840
Okay, so you can write as many as you want,

837
00:34:30.840 --> 00:34:34.203
but it would be for that one individual, okay?

838
00:34:35.250 --> 00:34:37.350
So those are the top three that people wanted

839
00:34:37.350 --> 00:34:38.550
to hear about.

840
00:34:38.550 --> 00:34:39.390
Dr. Connor.

841
00:34:39.390 --> 00:34:40.590
<v ->Thank you David.</v>

842
00:34:40.590 --> 00:34:42.183
So a couple good questions here

843
00:34:42.183 --> 00:34:44.010
regarding tuberculosis treatment.

844
00:34:44.010 --> 00:34:46.860
How is Rifampin different from Rifapentine?

845
00:34:46.860 --> 00:34:48.690
Very good question.

846
00:34:48.690 --> 00:34:51.270
Rifapentine has a longer half-life

847
00:34:51.270 --> 00:34:54.930
and it has a lower MIC from Mycobacterium tuberculosis.

848
00:34:54.930 --> 00:34:57.120
It also has a higher intracellular versus

849
00:34:57.120 --> 00:34:58.650
extracellular ratio.

850
00:34:58.650 --> 00:34:59.760
All of these combined

851
00:34:59.760 --> 00:35:02.040
to make it a more effective medication.

852
00:35:02.040 --> 00:35:03.183
So very good question.

853
00:35:05.370 --> 00:35:08.070
How would you tell blasto from histo on the boards?

854
00:35:08.070 --> 00:35:09.760
Also a very good question.

855
00:35:09.760 --> 00:35:11.820
You're probably not gonna see both of them

856
00:35:11.820 --> 00:35:13.383
listed as options.

857
00:35:14.370 --> 00:35:17.730
If they describe a patient with an incidental finding

858
00:35:17.730 --> 00:35:20.610
who grew up in the Ohio River Valley area,

859
00:35:20.610 --> 00:35:24.003
you would get either histo or blasto asked,

860
00:35:25.380 --> 00:35:26.430
but you probably wouldn't see both.

861
00:35:26.430 --> 00:35:27.540
So that's a good question.

862
00:35:27.540 --> 00:35:30.510
I will say histo tends to be more

863
00:35:30.510 --> 00:35:35.130
with bird and bat droppings

864
00:35:35.130 --> 00:35:37.530
and blasto tends to live in the soil.

865
00:35:37.530 --> 00:35:40.323
So if you went hiking through a forest,

866
00:35:41.870 --> 00:35:45.933
you might be more likely to develop blasto.

867
00:35:48.210 --> 00:35:50.700
First generation antihistamines,

868
00:35:50.700 --> 00:35:52.740
why for upper airway cough syndrome,

869
00:35:52.740 --> 00:35:54.450
because they're more sedating

870
00:35:54.450 --> 00:35:56.580
so they're more likely to reduce the cough.

871
00:35:56.580 --> 00:36:00.510
Although overall for rhinitis we do prefer the

872
00:36:00.510 --> 00:36:04.680
less sedating secondary antihistamines.

873
00:36:04.680 --> 00:36:08.880
Lastly for that talk, what about people who get a cough

874
00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:10.410
after they eat.

875
00:36:10.410 --> 00:36:13.500
That is post gustatory or vasomotor rhinitis,

876
00:36:13.500 --> 00:36:16.020
very common, especially in elderly patients.

877
00:36:16.020 --> 00:36:18.660
They can't eat anything without the drip and the cough.

878
00:36:18.660 --> 00:36:21.300
So we basically treat them with Atrovent,

879
00:36:21.300 --> 00:36:24.510
which is ipratropium bromide nasal spray

880
00:36:24.510 --> 00:36:28.023
prior to eating and that helps dry them up.

881
00:36:30.180 --> 00:36:31.050
<v ->I'm gonna take one more.</v>

882
00:36:31.050 --> 00:36:34.860
As Dr. Connor is shifting, this is an important one.

883
00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:36.930
Does insurance typically cover prep?

884
00:36:36.930 --> 00:36:39.060
It covers a hundred percent of it.

885
00:36:39.060 --> 00:36:41.610
It's a level A recommendation from the USPSTF.

886
00:36:41.610 --> 00:36:42.443
So your insurance has to cover it.

887
00:36:42.443 --> 00:36:44.820
Yeah, all the testings included as well.

888
00:36:44.820 --> 00:36:48.630
So it usually is covered at zero cost.

889
00:36:48.630 --> 00:36:52.410
The biggest issue I'm seeing now with patients with prep

890
00:36:52.410 --> 00:36:54.720
is really ridiculous to me is

891
00:36:54.720 --> 00:36:56.370
that insurance companies will not allow

892
00:36:56.370 --> 00:36:58.323
more than a 30 day dispense.

893
00:36:59.160 --> 00:37:01.590
And for many insurances they won't

894
00:37:01.590 --> 00:37:03.210
allow it to be on auto refill.

895
00:37:03.210 --> 00:37:06.120
I have one patient right now whose pharmacist is calling him

896
00:37:06.120 --> 00:37:09.900
every single month to remind him to refill the prep.

897
00:37:09.900 --> 00:37:11.640
And I'm like, that is crazy.

898
00:37:11.640 --> 00:37:14.280
So yes, insurance will cover all of this

899
00:37:14.280 --> 00:37:18.450
and if you just Google the correct codes

900
00:37:18.450 --> 00:37:20.670
to make sure you're coding this correctly,

901
00:37:20.670 --> 00:37:22.560
it's never an issue.

902
00:37:22.560 --> 00:37:24.300
It should be zero out of pocket

903
00:37:24.300 --> 00:37:26.880
for almost every patient with any insurance

904
00:37:26.880 --> 00:37:27.900
'cause it's a level A

905
00:37:27.900 --> 00:37:30.720
and that's why the USPSTF is coming to us

906
00:37:30.720 --> 00:37:32.970
to say you are the ones at the frontline,

907
00:37:32.970 --> 00:37:34.380
primary care physicians,

908
00:37:34.380 --> 00:37:36.027
you need to be having this discussion with patient.

909
00:37:36.027 --> 00:37:39.720
And that's why I gave you those three kind of lead-ins to

910
00:37:39.720 --> 00:37:41.250
how that discussion may go.

911
00:37:41.250 --> 00:37:42.240
Okay, Dr. Connor?

912
00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:43.290
<v ->Okay, thank you.</v>

913
00:37:43.290 --> 00:37:46.650
So good question about someone who has sleep apnea,

914
00:37:46.650 --> 00:37:47.970
they're treated with their CPAP,

915
00:37:47.970 --> 00:37:50.790
but they're still having excessive daytime fatigue.

916
00:37:50.790 --> 00:37:52.590
Well that's where medications come in.

917
00:37:52.590 --> 00:37:57.590
So modafinil and similar drugs are, Provigil, Nuvigil,

918
00:37:58.110 --> 00:37:59.610
there's a whole host of them out now.

919
00:37:59.610 --> 00:38:02.460
They basically stimulate the reticular activating system in

920
00:38:02.460 --> 00:38:05.250
the brain to keep the patient from falling asleep.

921
00:38:05.250 --> 00:38:08.310
So those are stimulant type drugs

922
00:38:08.310 --> 00:38:10.395
that you would prescribe in the case.

923
00:38:10.395 --> 00:38:13.683
We also use 'em for sleep shift work disorder,

924
00:38:14.610 --> 00:38:15.720
same type of drugs.

925
00:38:15.720 --> 00:38:17.550
So that would be what you would do.

926
00:38:17.550 --> 00:38:19.140
And someone asked about this,

927
00:38:19.140 --> 00:38:22.320
I failed to mention it actually during the talk,

928
00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:26.743
but regarding lung cancer screening with the low dose CT,

929
00:38:28.200 --> 00:38:31.380
if the patient has successfully quit smoking

930
00:38:31.380 --> 00:38:35.700
for 15 years or more, then you can stop the screening.

931
00:38:35.700 --> 00:38:38.190
So again, that screening is age 50

932
00:38:38.190 --> 00:38:41.800
or higher with a 20 pack year history of smoking

933
00:38:42.810 --> 00:38:47.700
and you can stop the screening if they quit smoking

934
00:38:47.700 --> 00:38:49.470
for 15 years.

935
00:38:49.470 --> 00:38:52.920
<v ->I'm gonna ask Jonathan to go ahead and get started.</v>

936
00:38:52.920 --> 00:38:53.943
<v ->Okay, thank you.</v>

937
00:38:55.380 --> 00:38:56.400
Alright, for heart failure,

938
00:38:56.400 --> 00:38:59.010
there are only a couple that I'll address right here.

939
00:38:59.010 --> 00:39:01.680
There are a bunch that I'll address on the app here.

940
00:39:01.680 --> 00:39:04.800
The, let's see, the one for heart failure patients.

941
00:39:04.800 --> 00:39:07.350
Do I add an ACE or a ARB even if a patient

942
00:39:07.350 --> 00:39:09.030
doesn't have hypertension

943
00:39:09.030 --> 00:39:10.470
and an SGLT2 inhibitor,

944
00:39:10.470 --> 00:39:13.170
even if the patient doesn't have diabetes.

945
00:39:13.170 --> 00:39:14.319
And the answer is yes.

946
00:39:14.319 --> 00:39:17.820
When we're thinking about heart failure management,

947
00:39:17.820 --> 00:39:20.970
guideline directed medical therapy is really irrespective

948
00:39:20.970 --> 00:39:23.310
of blood pressure and granted,

949
00:39:23.310 --> 00:39:25.140
a lot of patients with heart failure

950
00:39:25.140 --> 00:39:26.250
are gonna have hypertension.

951
00:39:26.250 --> 00:39:30.030
So we're wanting some decrease in blood pressure as well.

952
00:39:30.030 --> 00:39:32.250
There's also a good chunk of patients with heart failure

953
00:39:32.250 --> 00:39:33.450
who are gonna be normotensive,

954
00:39:33.450 --> 00:39:35.310
if not even a bit on the lower side.

955
00:39:35.310 --> 00:39:38.160
And we're basically trying to juggle

956
00:39:38.160 --> 00:39:40.590
wanting to start a beta blocker, wanting to start an ACE

957
00:39:40.590 --> 00:39:42.693
or ARB, wanting to start an MRA,

958
00:39:42.693 --> 00:39:44.640
spironolactone or plerinone,

959
00:39:44.640 --> 00:39:46.500
but not having a blood pressure to do it.

960
00:39:46.500 --> 00:39:50.250
So you may find yourself juggling tiny doses

961
00:39:50.250 --> 00:39:53.010
and the key thing is that even tiny doses,

962
00:39:53.010 --> 00:39:55.170
lisinopril two and a half milligrams,

963
00:39:55.170 --> 00:39:58.260
metoprolol succinate 12.5 milligrams daily,

964
00:39:58.260 --> 00:40:00.230
a wee little dose, 12 and a half milligrams

965
00:40:00.230 --> 00:40:01.560
of spironolactone.

966
00:40:01.560 --> 00:40:03.570
Maybe all that the patient and their blood pressure

967
00:40:03.570 --> 00:40:04.980
are going to tolerate.

968
00:40:04.980 --> 00:40:07.050
Still the goal is to make sure to have,

969
00:40:07.050 --> 00:40:09.360
especially for reduced ejection fraction, still to have

970
00:40:09.360 --> 00:40:13.320
as many elements of GDMT on board as possible,

971
00:40:13.320 --> 00:40:16.950
even if it means a little tiny bit of each drug as opposed

972
00:40:16.950 --> 00:40:19.620
to a big dose of one drug and none of the others.

973
00:40:19.620 --> 00:40:23.340
So the goal is always as many elements of GDMT

974
00:40:23.340 --> 00:40:27.023
as possible, even if you have to adjust them down,

975
00:40:27.023 --> 00:40:29.520
taper down to wee little doses to be able

976
00:40:29.520 --> 00:40:31.323
to tolerate blood pressure.

977
00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:35.760
<v ->I'm gonna do a couple here.</v>

978
00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:38.190
Do you do pap smears in virgins?

979
00:40:38.190 --> 00:40:42.630
Okay, so screening for cervical cancer is the question here.

980
00:40:42.630 --> 00:40:44.370
The current published guidelines

981
00:40:44.370 --> 00:40:47.583
by both the American Cancer Society, the USPSTF,

982
00:40:48.480 --> 00:40:52.590
and both ACOG and the ASCCP,

983
00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:54.660
the guidelines apply to individuals

984
00:40:54.660 --> 00:40:58.170
who have never engaged in sexual activity as well.

985
00:40:58.170 --> 00:40:59.820
Now with any screening test,

986
00:40:59.820 --> 00:41:02.610
of course you're gonna have a discussion with the patient,

987
00:41:02.610 --> 00:41:04.253
do you need to be screened?

988
00:41:04.253 --> 00:41:08.580
However, the current published guidelines are regardless

989
00:41:08.580 --> 00:41:10.320
of sexual activity

990
00:41:10.320 --> 00:41:12.570
and the American Cancer Society is recommending

991
00:41:12.570 --> 00:41:14.580
starting at age 25,

992
00:41:14.580 --> 00:41:17.430
the other published guidelines recommend starting at 21.

993
00:41:17.430 --> 00:41:20.820
But as I said, the USPSTF is currently looking at this.

994
00:41:20.820 --> 00:41:23.670
And the data, which led to the published guidelines

995
00:41:23.670 --> 00:41:28.327
from 2012 by the ASCCP and ACOG both

996
00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:32.070
suggested that you could wait until 25 to start.

997
00:41:32.070 --> 00:41:36.720
But as I said, the consensus panel felt uncomfortable

998
00:41:36.720 --> 00:41:38.670
delaying until age 25.

999
00:41:38.670 --> 00:41:42.120
But that is the guidelines

1000
00:41:42.120 --> 00:41:44.370
are regardless of sexual activity.

1001
00:41:44.370 --> 00:41:48.750
Now, there was a question here about

1002
00:41:48.750 --> 00:41:52.710
if you're starting hormone therapy in postmenopausal women.

1003
00:41:52.710 --> 00:41:55.300
Remember the only indication is for

1004
00:41:57.570 --> 00:42:02.570
vasomotor symptoms to use systemic hormone therapy.

1005
00:42:02.640 --> 00:42:05.520
If you are starting it, during that first year,

1006
00:42:05.520 --> 00:42:08.040
you will have some intermittent bleeding.

1007
00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:09.870
If there is bleeding that persists

1008
00:42:09.870 --> 00:42:12.840
beyond the first 12 months,

1009
00:42:12.840 --> 00:42:15.420
those individuals should be evaluated.

1010
00:42:15.420 --> 00:42:16.710
Now you can evaluate

1011
00:42:16.710 --> 00:42:19.650
with either transvaginal sonography looking at endometrial

1012
00:42:19.650 --> 00:42:23.550
thickness or with an endometrial biopsy.

1013
00:42:23.550 --> 00:42:26.310
The correct answer for the examination is to start

1014
00:42:26.310 --> 00:42:27.840
with the transvaginal ultrasound.

1015
00:42:27.840 --> 00:42:30.840
I will tell you in practice though, the patient's there,

1016
00:42:30.840 --> 00:42:33.990
they have postmenopausal bleeding, whether they are on HT

1017
00:42:33.990 --> 00:42:37.050
or not, I do an endometrial biopsy.

1018
00:42:37.050 --> 00:42:38.880
It's just I don't need to reappoint them

1019
00:42:38.880 --> 00:42:42.870
and there's no reason to create additional angst

1020
00:42:42.870 --> 00:42:45.960
by coming in for this procedure.

1021
00:42:45.960 --> 00:42:50.347
Now, using a pipelle in terms of an endometrial biopsy,

1022
00:42:50.347 --> 00:42:53.640
it is an uncomfortable procedure from the standpoint

1023
00:42:53.640 --> 00:42:56.550
that you're gonna need to dilate the cervix just a tad.

1024
00:42:56.550 --> 00:43:00.630
And any implement instrumentation

1025
00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:03.990
of the uterus causes fairly significant cramps.

1026
00:43:03.990 --> 00:43:05.370
400 of ibuprofen.

1027
00:43:05.370 --> 00:43:09.600
If they are very apprehensive, then a small amount,

1028
00:43:09.600 --> 00:43:11.640
a very small dose of a benzodiazepine

1029
00:43:11.640 --> 00:43:13.080
and I will reappoint them.

1030
00:43:13.080 --> 00:43:14.730
They take that once they get to the office

1031
00:43:14.730 --> 00:43:17.400
and typically that will be sufficient.

1032
00:43:17.400 --> 00:43:19.890
Now, and the other one here related

1033
00:43:19.890 --> 00:43:22.560
to HT was when do you stop it?

1034
00:43:22.560 --> 00:43:25.293
Okay, that's the point I wanted to make.

1035
00:43:26.130 --> 00:43:27.093
You don't.

1036
00:43:28.650 --> 00:43:29.483
Okay?

1037
00:43:29.483 --> 00:43:32.730
If they are continuing with vasomotor symptoms,

1038
00:43:32.730 --> 00:43:35.430
the recommendation is you continue it.

1039
00:43:35.430 --> 00:43:37.890
Now, two years of therapy

1040
00:43:37.890 --> 00:43:40.110
is when I start having a discussion about, on an

1041
00:43:40.110 --> 00:43:43.077
annual basis, risk-benefit.

1042
00:43:43.077 --> 00:43:45.330
As we discussed on the very first day,

1043
00:43:45.330 --> 00:43:48.210
remember in the Women's Health Initiative, it was the arm

1044
00:43:48.210 --> 00:43:50.464
of women who were both on progesterone

1045
00:43:50.464 --> 00:43:52.800
and estrogen where the risk

1046
00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:54.780
of breast cancer started going up.

1047
00:43:54.780 --> 00:43:56.670
18 years of follow-up data shows that

1048
00:43:56.670 --> 00:43:59.340
that risk starts going up at five to seven years.

1049
00:43:59.340 --> 00:44:03.000
And it was an increased risk of breast cancer,

1050
00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.760
not breast cancer deaths.

1051
00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:09.630
So I have patients well into their seventies who are like,

1052
00:44:09.630 --> 00:44:13.080
I'm not coming off, I feel better.

1053
00:44:13.080 --> 00:44:16.350
Now, do you stop it abruptly or do you titrate them off?

1054
00:44:16.350 --> 00:44:18.750
It doesn't matter because if they're gonna have return

1055
00:44:18.750 --> 00:44:21.600
of hot flashes, they have the return of hot flashes.

1056
00:44:21.600 --> 00:44:23.490
If in your end of one studies you find

1057
00:44:23.490 --> 00:44:26.340
that tapering does a better job, then taper them.

1058
00:44:26.340 --> 00:44:27.990
And then the last question was about, I wanted

1059
00:44:27.990 --> 00:44:29.700
to follow up on here was about clonidine.

1060
00:44:29.700 --> 00:44:31.470
You didn't see that up there.

1061
00:44:31.470 --> 00:44:33.870
That really has fallen out of favor in terms of use

1062
00:44:33.870 --> 00:44:36.210
for postmenopausal vasomotor symptoms.

1063
00:44:36.210 --> 00:44:39.180
If somebody's on it and it works for them, that's fine,

1064
00:44:39.180 --> 00:44:41.356
but typically I'm using an SSRI

1065
00:44:41.356 --> 00:44:43.650
or an SNRI as an alternative.

1066
00:44:43.650 --> 00:44:46.500
Keeping in mind that for vasomotor symptoms,

1067
00:44:46.500 --> 00:44:49.830
hormone therapy, lowest dose that is tolerable

1068
00:44:49.830 --> 00:44:52.290
and gets rid of their symptoms is going

1069
00:44:52.290 --> 00:44:53.763
to be more effective.

1070
00:44:54.660 --> 00:44:55.493
Dr. Heinrich?

1071
00:44:55.493 --> 00:44:57.120
<v ->Yeah, so I can take a couple here.</v>

1072
00:44:58.020 --> 00:45:00.750
Couple regarding ECT that I can kind of lump together.

1073
00:45:00.750 --> 00:45:03.090
One is, where does ECT fit in my kind

1074
00:45:03.090 --> 00:45:04.590
of therapeutic algorithm?

1075
00:45:04.590 --> 00:45:07.833
When do I call out ECT and speaking to a patient?

1076
00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:10.950
It depends.

1077
00:45:10.950 --> 00:45:12.690
There isn't really a line that I cross

1078
00:45:12.690 --> 00:45:14.760
with any specific patient when I get there.

1079
00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:17.940
If I'm treating the depression

1080
00:45:17.940 --> 00:45:20.370
and as I mentioned, monitoring the response

1081
00:45:20.370 --> 00:45:22.050
and they're moving forward,

1082
00:45:22.050 --> 00:45:24.480
I pretty much continue along the path I'm doing until

1083
00:45:24.480 --> 00:45:26.580
that aspect is maximized.

1084
00:45:26.580 --> 00:45:28.650
If, however, when I'm dealing with a patient

1085
00:45:28.650 --> 00:45:30.690
and I notice the treatment's not working

1086
00:45:30.690 --> 00:45:34.196
or the patient's getting worse, then ECT can often,

1087
00:45:34.196 --> 00:45:38.073
often come up in a discussion as therapeutic options.

1088
00:45:39.390 --> 00:45:43.440
Where I will definitely consider ECT as a first line are

1089
00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:46.770
for those patients that have life-threatening conditions

1090
00:45:46.770 --> 00:45:48.750
as a result of their depression

1091
00:45:48.750 --> 00:45:51.210
that require a very quick response.

1092
00:45:51.210 --> 00:45:53.310
The most common is a failure to thrive.

1093
00:45:53.310 --> 00:45:56.010
A geriatric patient with profound depression stops eating,

1094
00:45:56.010 --> 00:45:57.960
stops engaging.

1095
00:45:57.960 --> 00:46:02.250
Those patients are often referred to ECT very rapidly.

1096
00:46:02.250 --> 00:46:05.910
And as I mentioned, the psychotic depression as well.

1097
00:46:05.910 --> 00:46:08.100
And the other question related

1098
00:46:08.100 --> 00:46:11.370
to ECT is why isn't it used more often?

1099
00:46:11.370 --> 00:46:14.250
Well, there's an infrastructure behind ECT.

1100
00:46:14.250 --> 00:46:16.020
Often ECT is initiated

1101
00:46:16.020 --> 00:46:17.730
as a psychiatric inpatient.

1102
00:46:17.730 --> 00:46:20.190
So there's that stigma associated with that,

1103
00:46:20.190 --> 00:46:22.000
just to make sure they tolerate it

1104
00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:26.191
and it's just, it's difficult.

1105
00:46:26.191 --> 00:46:28.710
ECT at our institution is done at six in the morning.

1106
00:46:28.710 --> 00:46:31.350
So patients have to get there at four in the morning to go

1107
00:46:31.350 --> 00:46:32.643
through all their stuff.

1108
00:46:34.140 --> 00:46:36.750
And then the really impressive thing though,

1109
00:46:36.750 --> 00:46:39.930
despite the infrastructure, despite the work inherent

1110
00:46:39.930 --> 00:46:43.230
for the patient, once they do it, they love it

1111
00:46:43.230 --> 00:46:44.640
and don't leave it

1112
00:46:44.640 --> 00:46:47.340
because it's worked so well.

1113
00:46:47.340 --> 00:46:49.260
They often will do the maintenance therapy.

1114
00:46:49.260 --> 00:46:50.310
So we'll do it.

1115
00:46:50.310 --> 00:46:53.190
The typical course of ECT is three times a week

1116
00:46:53.190 --> 00:46:56.220
until you get the response and remission.

1117
00:46:56.220 --> 00:46:59.100
That usually takes about six treatments.

1118
00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:01.560
Then you'll break it down to do it about once a week

1119
00:47:01.560 --> 00:47:02.670
and then once a month

1120
00:47:02.670 --> 00:47:04.650
and you'll stretch it out as much as you can.

1121
00:47:04.650 --> 00:47:07.110
But patients will continue to come back.

1122
00:47:07.110 --> 00:47:08.040
During this whole time,

1123
00:47:08.040 --> 00:47:09.810
it's important to realize they're still getting their

1124
00:47:09.810 --> 00:47:11.730
pharmacotherapy as well.

1125
00:47:11.730 --> 00:47:14.343
The ECT is just kind of maintaining that.

1126
00:47:15.690 --> 00:47:17.910
One of the other really nice sophisticated questions

1127
00:47:17.910 --> 00:47:20.520
that was asked was, what's the role

1128
00:47:20.520 --> 00:47:24.450
of the geriatric depression scale when you're screening

1129
00:47:24.450 --> 00:47:26.310
for depression in the elderly?

1130
00:47:26.310 --> 00:47:28.500
The concept of the geriatric depression scale,

1131
00:47:28.500 --> 00:47:30.570
for those of you that are not familiar with it,

1132
00:47:30.570 --> 00:47:32.010
as I alluded to in my talk,

1133
00:47:32.010 --> 00:47:35.190
depressed, elderly patients focus on somatic complaints.

1134
00:47:35.190 --> 00:47:38.223
Often this attempts to address that.

1135
00:47:39.930 --> 00:47:42.120
I tend to stick with the PHQ-9,

1136
00:47:42.120 --> 00:47:44.490
which has been validated in the elderly,

1137
00:47:44.490 --> 00:47:47.700
but that's primarily from a process standpoint.

1138
00:47:47.700 --> 00:47:51.180
I don't want multiple scales making my clinic more complex.

1139
00:47:51.180 --> 00:47:54.060
I want one scale that everybody knows to go to.

1140
00:47:54.060 --> 00:47:56.040
The other thing that's really nice about

1141
00:47:56.961 --> 00:48:00.120
the PHQ-9 that I mentioned, it can be the same scale

1142
00:48:00.120 --> 00:48:02.760
I used to follow somebody longitudinally

1143
00:48:02.760 --> 00:48:05.040
and get them into remission and response.

1144
00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:08.220
So I tend to stick with the PHQ-9.

1145
00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:10.240
You're not gonna go wrong with the GDS

1146
00:48:11.120 --> 00:48:11.953
with no question at all.

1147
00:48:11.953 --> 00:48:13.830
It's validated and appropriate,

1148
00:48:13.830 --> 00:48:16.143
but I tend to stick with the PHQ.

1149
00:48:19.860 --> 00:48:22.260
And then a question about antidepressants,

1150
00:48:22.260 --> 00:48:25.230
when making a switch, how we titrate.

1151
00:48:25.230 --> 00:48:27.660
Kind of depends on the setting in which you're watching the

1152
00:48:27.660 --> 00:48:30.270
patient and and managing the patient.

1153
00:48:30.270 --> 00:48:32.640
Again, this is more of an art than a science.

1154
00:48:32.640 --> 00:48:33.840
There's no one way to do it.

1155
00:48:33.840 --> 00:48:35.400
I have a colleague that stops one

1156
00:48:35.400 --> 00:48:38.040
and starts the other like that.

1157
00:48:38.040 --> 00:48:39.210
I tend not to do that.

1158
00:48:39.210 --> 00:48:42.590
I tend to taper one of the antidepressants down to about 50%

1159
00:48:42.590 --> 00:48:46.230
of the typical dose and then I'll initiate the second one,

1160
00:48:46.230 --> 00:48:47.790
watch for any kind of side effects

1161
00:48:47.790 --> 00:48:50.670
and then I'll cross taper by 25%.

1162
00:48:50.670 --> 00:48:51.660
Kind of increase one,

1163
00:48:51.660 --> 00:48:54.180
decrease the other until I get where we're at.

1164
00:48:54.180 --> 00:48:55.440
And you always know,

1165
00:48:55.440 --> 00:48:57.210
you can stop the taper if things are going

1166
00:48:57.210 --> 00:48:59.280
or slow things down at the same time.

1167
00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:00.570
<v ->Dr. Fern, however, you wanna take one</v>

1168
00:49:00.570 --> 00:49:02.190
or two more and then we're gonna take a break.

1169
00:49:02.190 --> 00:49:04.350
<v ->The one question which is important</v>

1170
00:49:04.350 --> 00:49:06.630
to note predictive timeframe for CHADS2-VASc.

1171
00:49:06.630 --> 00:49:09.298
The stroke risk when you're looking at CHADS2

1172
00:49:09.298 --> 00:49:12.480
or CHADS2-VASc scores is an annual stroke risk.

1173
00:49:12.480 --> 00:49:15.900
And so you're looking at basically the annual bleeding risk

1174
00:49:15.900 --> 00:49:18.030
compared to an annual stroke risk.

1175
00:49:18.030 --> 00:49:19.650
And even though you may look at it

1176
00:49:19.650 --> 00:49:22.740
and say, okay, the numbers for bleeding are lower

1177
00:49:22.740 --> 00:49:25.230
or they're relatively low numbers,

1178
00:49:25.230 --> 00:49:26.760
when we're talking about bleeding risk

1179
00:49:26.760 --> 00:49:29.970
with an anticoagulant, it is typically not I cut my finger

1180
00:49:29.970 --> 00:49:32.580
and it took an extra few minutes for it to quit bleeding.

1181
00:49:32.580 --> 00:49:34.620
It's I had an intra cerebral bleed,

1182
00:49:34.620 --> 00:49:36.690
a life-threatening gastrointestinal bleed.

1183
00:49:36.690 --> 00:49:38.970
So even though the numbers are relatively low,

1184
00:49:38.970 --> 00:49:42.270
the things that are being counted are quite worrisome.

1185
00:49:42.270 --> 00:49:45.300
And then final point, the question about

1186
00:49:45.300 --> 00:49:49.710
the vascular disease on CHADS2-VASc,

1187
00:49:49.710 --> 00:49:52.260
it is, technically, it's still kind of vague.

1188
00:49:52.260 --> 00:49:53.250
It's coronary artery disease,

1189
00:49:53.250 --> 00:49:56.760
peripheral artery disease or aortic atherosclerosis.

1190
00:49:56.760 --> 00:50:00.030
And aortic atherosclerosis can be diagnosed simply

1191
00:50:00.030 --> 00:50:01.350
by a chest x-ray.

1192
00:50:01.350 --> 00:50:03.870
If you see on someone's chest X-ray, you can see a nice ring

1193
00:50:03.870 --> 00:50:05.580
of calcium around their aorta.

1194
00:50:05.580 --> 00:50:08.730
That would count if you're looking at a CHADS2-VASc score

1195
00:50:08.730 --> 00:50:11.193
as evidence of atherosclerotic disease.

1196
00:50:12.300 --> 00:50:14.883
<v ->Okay, I'm gonna start with a few questions here.</v>

1197
00:50:15.720 --> 00:50:18.240
One of them I want to follow up from the last talk,

1198
00:50:18.240 --> 00:50:22.500
which was about Veozah, which is a treatment for moderate

1199
00:50:22.500 --> 00:50:24.570
to severe vasomotor symptoms.

1200
00:50:24.570 --> 00:50:27.450
This is a brand new drug, it's actually a new class

1201
00:50:27.450 --> 00:50:30.030
of drugs called a neurokinin inhibitor.

1202
00:50:30.030 --> 00:50:31.830
That will not be on the exam.

1203
00:50:31.830 --> 00:50:33.660
It's very expensive though.

1204
00:50:33.660 --> 00:50:36.570
It runs about $550 per month.

1205
00:50:36.570 --> 00:50:39.360
So somebody asks me, well what do you think about it?

1206
00:50:39.360 --> 00:50:41.820
The data shows that it does work.

1207
00:50:41.820 --> 00:50:44.550
It could be potentially helpful for those who cannot,

1208
00:50:44.550 --> 00:50:46.200
who are not candidates for

1209
00:50:46.200 --> 00:50:48.510
or could not tolerate an estrogen.

1210
00:50:48.510 --> 00:50:52.290
But right now, like many things that are new,

1211
00:50:52.290 --> 00:50:54.720
the cost is a big issue.

1212
00:50:54.720 --> 00:50:58.443
Okay, a couple questions from the second presentation.

1213
00:51:00.900 --> 00:51:04.650
So why not store pumped breast milk from the infected breast

1214
00:51:04.650 --> 00:51:08.100
and mastitis, especially if it's safe to continue feeding?

1215
00:51:08.100 --> 00:51:10.890
Because if it's not stored properly,

1216
00:51:10.890 --> 00:51:14.520
you could then have really contaminated milk.

1217
00:51:14.520 --> 00:51:17.400
So the issue is not just that it's infected,

1218
00:51:17.400 --> 00:51:20.100
it's just making sure that there's appropriate storage.

1219
00:51:20.100 --> 00:51:21.120
So the recommendation is

1220
00:51:21.120 --> 00:51:25.620
to not in general store milk from the infected

1221
00:51:25.620 --> 00:51:27.213
affected breast.

1222
00:51:28.050 --> 00:51:30.185
Is it still recommended to get a pregnancy test

1223
00:51:30.185 --> 00:51:32.490
before starting OCPs?

1224
00:51:32.490 --> 00:51:34.440
Well if there's any question about the patient being

1225
00:51:34.440 --> 00:51:36.030
pregnant, yes.

1226
00:51:36.030 --> 00:51:39.540
However, if they're on continuous oral contraceptives

1227
00:51:39.540 --> 00:51:42.870
and/or any other form of birth control,

1228
00:51:42.870 --> 00:51:47.670
then it is not required to get prior to starting them.

1229
00:51:47.670 --> 00:51:50.040
Any concerns about a vaginal delivery

1230
00:51:50.040 --> 00:51:52.950
after cesarean section on the boards?

1231
00:51:52.950 --> 00:51:53.783
No.

1232
00:51:53.783 --> 00:51:56.670
There is a choosing wisely actually from the Society

1233
00:51:56.670 --> 00:52:01.500
of Maternal Fetal Medicine that says even if you've had

1234
00:52:01.500 --> 00:52:04.203
a cesarean section times two,

1235
00:52:05.070 --> 00:52:07.050
that you are still a candidate

1236
00:52:07.050 --> 00:52:09.780
for vaginal birth after cesarean.

1237
00:52:09.780 --> 00:52:12.450
Now in counseling women

1238
00:52:12.450 --> 00:52:15.480
and consulting on women related to that, keep in mind

1239
00:52:15.480 --> 00:52:18.270
that this is a dynamic discussion.

1240
00:52:18.270 --> 00:52:21.480
You know, 16 weeks we're discussing should I have a vaginal

1241
00:52:21.480 --> 00:52:24.090
delivery or not after a cesarean?

1242
00:52:24.090 --> 00:52:26.130
Well what was the indication for the cesarean?

1243
00:52:26.130 --> 00:52:28.380
Well it was fetal presentation.

1244
00:52:28.380 --> 00:52:30.600
So if the fetal presentation was breached, you know

1245
00:52:30.600 --> 00:52:32.790
that's going to be an automatic c-section in the

1246
00:52:32.790 --> 00:52:34.140
21st century.

1247
00:52:34.140 --> 00:52:37.260
Nobody's going to do that, a breach delivery

1248
00:52:37.260 --> 00:52:40.680
unless it is an emergency, particularly if it's anything

1249
00:52:40.680 --> 00:52:43.050
but a frank breach.

1250
00:52:43.050 --> 00:52:47.040
However, if we move through the pregnancy

1251
00:52:47.040 --> 00:52:48.419
and all of a sudden we find

1252
00:52:48.419 --> 00:52:52.230
that some other complication arises,

1253
00:52:52.230 --> 00:52:55.680
we've got known fetal macrosomia secondary to diabetes,

1254
00:52:55.680 --> 00:52:56.910
it's not controlled,

1255
00:52:56.910 --> 00:53:01.560
before I proceeded with a trial of labor,

1256
00:53:01.560 --> 00:53:02.820
then I would be considering

1257
00:53:02.820 --> 00:53:05.850
with the patient is a cesarean section a safer way

1258
00:53:05.850 --> 00:53:10.650
to proceed or we'll allow things to go if things,

1259
00:53:10.650 --> 00:53:12.840
if we go into labor spontaneously.

1260
00:53:12.840 --> 00:53:15.210
However, if we are getting to the point where we have

1261
00:53:15.210 --> 00:53:19.140
to have an induction, then we're gonna reconsider,

1262
00:53:19.140 --> 00:53:20.910
is this the best thing to do?

1263
00:53:20.910 --> 00:53:23.100
The biggest one though comes down to

1264
00:53:23.100 --> 00:53:24.480
I've had uterine inertia

1265
00:53:24.480 --> 00:53:27.510
or what one would call failure to progress.

1266
00:53:27.510 --> 00:53:31.710
And remember today we don't diagnose failure to progress

1267
00:53:31.710 --> 00:53:35.280
until you've advanced to at least five to six centimeters.

1268
00:53:35.280 --> 00:53:36.390
Five to six centimeters.

1269
00:53:36.390 --> 00:53:38.220
Many of you're thinking, oh my gosh, if they got

1270
00:53:38.220 --> 00:53:40.290
beyond three then we would start diag-

1271
00:53:40.290 --> 00:53:43.500
No, it's five to six centimeters before we diagnose that.

1272
00:53:43.500 --> 00:53:45.120
So if they tell me, okay,

1273
00:53:45.120 --> 00:53:47.070
I had two previous cesareans

1274
00:53:47.070 --> 00:53:48.527
and this was secondary to the fact

1275
00:53:48.527 --> 00:53:51.000
that I had failure to progress.

1276
00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.340
They're a patient with a BMI of 40

1277
00:53:53.340 --> 00:53:56.640
and the baby's weighed six pounds, two ounces.

1278
00:53:56.640 --> 00:53:59.880
Mmm, I'm probably thinking this is probably a safer way

1279
00:53:59.880 --> 00:54:02.190
to proceed in repeating the cesarean than

1280
00:54:02.190 --> 00:54:04.050
proceeding with a vaginal delivery.

1281
00:54:04.050 --> 00:54:05.670
But it's a dynamic discussion

1282
00:54:05.670 --> 00:54:08.760
and the important thing for you to remember is

1283
00:54:08.760 --> 00:54:11.580
that on the exam, if that is asked,

1284
00:54:11.580 --> 00:54:14.820
the current recommendation is even in the presence of two,

1285
00:54:14.820 --> 00:54:17.580
you can still have a trial of labor.

1286
00:54:17.580 --> 00:54:20.790
And then what about role of testosterone treatment

1287
00:54:20.790 --> 00:54:23.940
for low libido in women and precautions?

1288
00:54:23.940 --> 00:54:27.483
Okay, so testosterone alone,

1289
00:54:28.680 --> 00:54:31.740
do not answer, use it on the exam

1290
00:54:31.740 --> 00:54:36.690
and in practice it is only used in combination with

1291
00:54:36.690 --> 00:54:39.690
vasomotor symptoms in terms

1292
00:54:39.690 --> 00:54:44.690
of improving sexual desire and sexual satisfaction.

1293
00:54:45.600 --> 00:54:47.850
So if somebody comes into the office

1294
00:54:47.850 --> 00:54:50.250
and they're saying, oh yeah, I'm on testosterone

1295
00:54:50.250 --> 00:54:52.350
and they don't have any vasomotor symptoms and

1296
00:54:52.350 --> 00:54:54.330
therefore they're not on estrogen,

1297
00:54:54.330 --> 00:54:57.480
the discussion is we need to come off of that.

1298
00:54:57.480 --> 00:55:01.320
Now are we dealing with hypoactive sexual desire disorder?

1299
00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:03.360
That's a whole different ball of wax in terms

1300
00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:04.770
of how we would treat that.

1301
00:55:04.770 --> 00:55:07.530
And that's what I would be exploring in terms of treatment.

1302
00:55:07.530 --> 00:55:09.150
But for the exam purposes

1303
00:55:09.150 --> 00:55:11.190
and for clinical practices,

1304
00:55:11.190 --> 00:55:14.790
testosterone alone is not indicated in women,

1305
00:55:14.790 --> 00:55:17.100
it is not FDA approved in women

1306
00:55:17.100 --> 00:55:20.490
and the only people who should be on it from an FDA

1307
00:55:20.490 --> 00:55:24.120
standpoint are women who are also on hormone therapy.

1308
00:55:24.120 --> 00:55:25.620
The only indication

1309
00:55:25.620 --> 00:55:29.160
for hormone therapy is vasomotor symptoms, okay?

1310
00:55:29.160 --> 00:55:30.420
So you've gotta have those

1311
00:55:30.420 --> 00:55:32.073
to get on hormone therapy.

1312
00:55:33.360 --> 00:55:34.193
Dr. Heinrich.

1313
00:55:34.193 --> 00:55:35.026
<v ->Sure.</v>

1314
00:55:36.090 --> 00:55:40.470
A lot of the questions on talk have to do with medications

1315
00:55:40.470 --> 00:55:43.320
and one of the big ones is if a patient is failing

1316
00:55:43.320 --> 00:55:45.540
to respond to the first medication of choice,

1317
00:55:45.540 --> 00:55:48.460
how do you decide what the next type of treatment is

1318
00:55:49.380 --> 00:55:52.710
specifically in regards to increasing the dose

1319
00:55:52.710 --> 00:55:55.470
or let's say switching to a different class of medication.

1320
00:55:55.470 --> 00:55:58.380
And that really has to do, for a board specific question,

1321
00:55:58.380 --> 00:56:00.209
on how the question is written.

1322
00:56:00.209 --> 00:56:03.990
If the patient has been demonstrating a kind

1323
00:56:03.990 --> 00:56:06.630
of gradual response, but a continued improvement

1324
00:56:06.630 --> 00:56:08.820
and you have a way to go up on the dose

1325
00:56:08.820 --> 00:56:10.200
of the current medication

1326
00:56:10.200 --> 00:56:12.870
and they're tolerating it, that's the right answer

1327
00:56:12.870 --> 00:56:15.060
to continue to increase the current medication

1328
00:56:15.060 --> 00:56:17.010
to the maximum tolerated dose as long

1329
00:56:17.010 --> 00:56:18.750
as they continue to respond.

1330
00:56:18.750 --> 00:56:22.443
If a patient has stopped responding to a certain medication,

1331
00:56:23.370 --> 00:56:26.907
increasing the dose and you've increased the dose once

1332
00:56:26.907 --> 00:56:30.090
and there isn't an a further increase in improvement

1333
00:56:30.090 --> 00:56:32.490
or rather improvement in the patient's symptoms,

1334
00:56:32.490 --> 00:56:35.370
then further increasing the medication is likely not

1335
00:56:35.370 --> 00:56:36.750
gonna be beneficial.

1336
00:56:36.750 --> 00:56:37.950
That's when either switching

1337
00:56:37.950 --> 00:56:42.453
or augmentation is the answer to go to on the test.

1338
00:56:44.041 --> 00:56:46.950
And then augmentation is again considered if a patient has a

1339
00:56:46.950 --> 00:56:49.320
partial response, you wanna add a medication

1340
00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:50.670
to continue that improvement.

1341
00:56:50.670 --> 00:56:54.033
If they've had no response, switching makes a lot of sense.

1342
00:56:55.320 --> 00:56:56.520
Whoop.

1343
00:56:56.520 --> 00:56:59.790
In regards to that same kind of question,

1344
00:56:59.790 --> 00:57:03.300
what is the best antidepressant for seniors and adolescents?

1345
00:57:03.300 --> 00:57:06.330
Those are primarily the SSRIs for both,

1346
00:57:06.330 --> 00:57:08.880
or they're my first go-to agents when I'm dealing within

1347
00:57:08.880 --> 00:57:10.893
both of those patient populations.

1348
00:57:12.570 --> 00:57:15.240
Another question is, this is the greatest question I think

1349
00:57:15.240 --> 00:57:16.410
I've been asked in years

1350
00:57:16.410 --> 00:57:18.720
and six of you have said something similar to this.

1351
00:57:18.720 --> 00:57:21.690
How is cyclothymia different than normal life?

1352
00:57:21.690 --> 00:57:24.180
Yeah, that's the one that you kind of hover around

1353
00:57:24.180 --> 00:57:26.190
this midline never getting hypomanic

1354
00:57:26.190 --> 00:57:27.960
and never giving depressed.

1355
00:57:27.960 --> 00:57:30.450
You got me there other than part

1356
00:57:30.450 --> 00:57:32.190
of the diagnostic criteria is an

1357
00:57:32.190 --> 00:57:34.080
impairment in one's function.

1358
00:57:34.080 --> 00:57:37.230
You may be fluctuating along that line like everybody else,

1359
00:57:37.230 --> 00:57:40.080
but for some reasoning it's hitting you differently,

1360
00:57:40.080 --> 00:57:41.640
it's impacting you differently

1361
00:57:41.640 --> 00:57:43.230
and you're not able to function.

1362
00:57:43.230 --> 00:57:45.060
That is really one of the key ways

1363
00:57:45.060 --> 00:57:49.140
that psychiatry in my mind, differentiates normal affect,

1364
00:57:49.140 --> 00:57:52.620
normal anxiety 'cause that's perfectly healthy

1365
00:57:52.620 --> 00:57:55.920
and helps us survive,

1366
00:57:55.920 --> 00:57:59.970
from pathological is its impact on your functioning.

1367
00:57:59.970 --> 00:58:02.910
I get very concerned when depression impacts functioning

1368
00:58:02.910 --> 00:58:04.500
or anxiety impacts functioning.

1369
00:58:04.500 --> 00:58:06.510
And that's how we come up with the idea that some

1370
00:58:06.510 --> 00:58:07.953
of it can be pathologic.

1371
00:58:09.300 --> 00:58:12.150
Another common question is a validated patient questionnaire

1372
00:58:12.150 --> 00:58:13.650
for bipolar patients.

1373
00:58:13.650 --> 00:58:16.080
Do any of you use the the mood disorder questionnaire

1374
00:58:16.080 --> 00:58:18.300
to help with that group of patients?

1375
00:58:18.300 --> 00:58:21.330
That's probably the one most commonly used in primary

1376
00:58:21.330 --> 00:58:23.490
care practices.

1377
00:58:23.490 --> 00:58:27.330
I tend to use that if I'm treating somebody for depression

1378
00:58:27.330 --> 00:58:29.670
and I've gone through this algorithm that I presented

1379
00:58:29.670 --> 00:58:31.590
and they're still not getting better.

1380
00:58:31.590 --> 00:58:34.110
Remember we question our diagnosis.

1381
00:58:34.110 --> 00:58:35.700
One of the diagnoses in somebody

1382
00:58:35.700 --> 00:58:37.530
with depression could be bipolar disorder.

1383
00:58:37.530 --> 00:58:39.750
So I'll do the mood disorder questionnaire

1384
00:58:39.750 --> 00:58:41.640
or if I get kind of a weird history

1385
00:58:41.640 --> 00:58:43.650
that I'm not really quite sure what's going on,

1386
00:58:43.650 --> 00:58:45.090
that's something I'll pull out.

1387
00:58:45.090 --> 00:58:47.230
It really does need to be confirmed by

1388
00:58:49.500 --> 00:58:51.033
an evaluation though.

1389
00:58:52.380 --> 00:58:55.140
Another common question here was how often

1390
00:58:55.140 --> 00:58:57.060
to check lithium levels.

1391
00:58:57.060 --> 00:58:59.630
Really, anytime you change a lithium dose, you want

1392
00:58:59.630 --> 00:59:00.960
to check a lithium level.

1393
00:59:00.960 --> 00:59:03.210
If you sense that somebody's remember let's,

1394
00:59:03.210 --> 00:59:05.850
so you check it at steady state is four days.

1395
00:59:05.850 --> 00:59:08.820
You check it before the morning or at evening dose just

1396
00:59:08.820 --> 00:59:10.890
before one of the two doses the patient

1397
00:59:10.890 --> 00:59:13.050
takes and you want it.

1398
00:59:13.050 --> 00:59:14.880
So you want to check a trough.

1399
00:59:14.880 --> 00:59:16.320
So anytime you change the dose,

1400
00:59:16.320 --> 00:59:17.880
you check it four days later.

1401
00:59:17.880 --> 00:59:19.830
Or if you get the sense the psychiatrist is

1402
00:59:19.830 --> 00:59:21.270
changing it, you're gonna check it.

1403
00:59:21.270 --> 00:59:25.150
Where you and I as a primary care provider may see it, is if

1404
00:59:26.100 --> 00:59:29.160
the renal function's changing, we notice on our labs

1405
00:59:29.160 --> 00:59:33.010
that their creatinine is increasing and the BUN

1406
00:59:33.960 --> 00:59:37.650
or the the GFR is going through the roof,

1407
00:59:37.650 --> 00:59:39.150
will wanna check a lithium

1408
00:59:39.150 --> 00:59:41.220
and not wait for the psychiatrist to check it

1409
00:59:41.220 --> 00:59:45.480
to make sure we're not having any issues of toxicity.

1410
00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:48.030
<v ->Several people have asked over the last couple days about</v>

1411
00:59:48.030 --> 00:59:49.623
questions on transgender care.

1412
00:59:50.730 --> 00:59:52.950
I think there may be one.

1413
00:59:52.950 --> 00:59:54.600
We had a discussion several weeks ago about

1414
00:59:54.600 --> 00:59:56.520
how we might include a bit more on that.

1415
00:59:56.520 --> 00:59:58.440
Here's, write these things down.

1416
00:59:58.440 --> 01:00:00.123
Here's what might be on there.

1417
01:00:01.080 --> 01:00:04.503
Number one, any intervention,

1418
01:00:07.200 --> 01:00:11.160
cross hormone therapy, surgical has been shown

1419
01:00:11.160 --> 01:00:12.363
to decrease dysphoria.

1420
01:00:14.490 --> 01:00:17.970
Two, if I'm on testosterone,

1421
01:00:17.970 --> 01:00:19.127
I'm gonna monitor the CBC

1422
01:00:19.127 --> 01:00:21.333
'cause I'm concerned about polycythemia.

1423
01:00:22.860 --> 01:00:27.660
Three, if I'm on estrogen, I'm gonna monitor the BMP

1424
01:00:27.660 --> 01:00:30.300
because frequently they're on spironolactone as well

1425
01:00:30.300 --> 01:00:33.060
as an anti-androgen and therefore they're at risk

1426
01:00:33.060 --> 01:00:36.840
for electrolyte abnormalities and renal dysfunction.

1427
01:00:36.840 --> 01:00:40.320
I think those are the ones you might see on there.

1428
01:00:40.320 --> 01:00:44.673
Otherwise you screen as for natal biology,

1429
01:00:46.080 --> 01:00:50.010
okay, any intervention with cross hormone therapy

1430
01:00:50.010 --> 01:00:53.883
or surgery has been shown to decrease dysphoria.

1431
01:00:55.470 --> 01:00:59.793
So I have top surgery, bottom surgery, facial feminization,

1432
01:01:00.900 --> 01:01:02.400
laser for removal of hair.

1433
01:01:02.400 --> 01:01:04.800
All those have been shown to decrease dysphoria.

1434
01:01:06.450 --> 01:01:08.760
If you are a trans male on testosterone,

1435
01:01:08.760 --> 01:01:10.200
the risk is polycythemia.

1436
01:01:10.200 --> 01:01:12.550
So they might give you a CBC which is elevated.

1437
01:01:13.410 --> 01:01:15.600
'Cause testosterone is like gasoline

1438
01:01:15.600 --> 01:01:18.034
for red blood cell production.

1439
01:01:18.034 --> 01:01:21.480
I can, in 15 years of doing transgender work,

1440
01:01:21.480 --> 01:01:24.540
I've had one patient where I've had to have blood,

1441
01:01:24.540 --> 01:01:27.750
have them had a unit of blood taken unlike other diseases

1442
01:01:27.750 --> 01:01:29.820
with polycythemia, which I've had

1443
01:01:29.820 --> 01:01:31.710
many times had to deal with.

1444
01:01:31.710 --> 01:01:34.680
And then from the estrogen standpoint, since most

1445
01:01:34.680 --> 01:01:36.390
of them are on spironolactone as well

1446
01:01:36.390 --> 01:01:39.240
as an anti-androgen, at 50 twice a day

1447
01:01:39.240 --> 01:01:41.010
to a hundred twice a day, they're at risk

1448
01:01:41.010 --> 01:01:43.770
for electrolyte abnormalities and/or renal dysfunction.

1449
01:01:43.770 --> 01:01:46.980
And therefore we follow on an annual basis,

1450
01:01:46.980 --> 01:01:49.653
the BMP.

1451
01:01:50.970 --> 01:01:54.540
Actually, unless the patient complains of something

1452
01:01:54.540 --> 01:01:56.700
after they're stable on their testosterone, their estrogen,

1453
01:01:56.700 --> 01:02:00.090
we don't keep repeating levels 'cause we treat the patient.

1454
01:02:00.090 --> 01:02:03.030
If you're subtherapeutic, you're not between a hundred,

1455
01:02:03.030 --> 01:02:05.190
200 picogram per mil on your estradiol.

1456
01:02:05.190 --> 01:02:06.630
You do not need to know that.

1457
01:02:06.630 --> 01:02:08.580
And you come in and your level is 70,

1458
01:02:08.580 --> 01:02:10.560
but you're like, I feel fabulous.

1459
01:02:10.560 --> 01:02:11.730
I've never felt better in my life.

1460
01:02:11.730 --> 01:02:15.030
We're not gonna increase your estrogen dose.

1461
01:02:15.030 --> 01:02:17.040
So typically we're only looking if we're concerned

1462
01:02:17.040 --> 01:02:18.240
about a toxic effect.

1463
01:02:18.240 --> 01:02:20.246
Okay, okay.

1464
01:02:20.246 --> 01:02:21.079
<v ->I'm ready.</v>
<v ->Go for it.</v>

1465
01:02:21.079 --> 01:02:21.933
<v ->I'm ready now.</v>

1466
01:02:23.610 --> 01:02:25.800
We had a question about the use of bupropion

1467
01:02:25.800 --> 01:02:28.230
or Wellbutrin in patients with ADHD.

1468
01:02:28.230 --> 01:02:29.640
They commented that they've been seeing more

1469
01:02:29.640 --> 01:02:31.800
and more patients being prescribed this.

1470
01:02:31.800 --> 01:02:34.410
There is an inherent logic for the use

1471
01:02:34.410 --> 01:02:37.020
of bupropion in patients with ADHD.

1472
01:02:37.020 --> 01:02:38.790
I have also used it.

1473
01:02:38.790 --> 01:02:41.430
The data, however, is pretty sketchy at this point

1474
01:02:41.430 --> 01:02:43.380
of its true efficacy.

1475
01:02:43.380 --> 01:02:46.050
That being said, it certainly does,

1476
01:02:46.050 --> 01:02:49.740
it's there along with the non-stimulants as something

1477
01:02:49.740 --> 01:02:53.550
that potentially can be tried, especially for individuals

1478
01:02:53.550 --> 01:02:56.010
that may have some substance use issues in the past.

1479
01:02:56.010 --> 01:02:59.490
So if they failed to norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors,

1480
01:02:59.490 --> 01:03:00.840
this may be something to try.

1481
01:03:00.840 --> 01:03:03.303
But the data just truly isn't all there yet.

1482
01:03:05.280 --> 01:03:07.200
Related actually to the depression talk,

1483
01:03:07.200 --> 01:03:08.580
but I kind of wanna address it

1484
01:03:08.580 --> 01:03:10.110
because it's a very common concern

1485
01:03:10.110 --> 01:03:11.850
of primary care providers.

1486
01:03:11.850 --> 01:03:13.020
Is patients coming

1487
01:03:13.020 --> 01:03:14.970
to you requesting genetic testing when their

1488
01:03:14.970 --> 01:03:17.340
antidepressants aren't working?

1489
01:03:17.340 --> 01:03:18.173
There's the (indistinct).

1490
01:03:18.173 --> 01:03:19.760
Have you guys had that experience?

1491
01:03:20.730 --> 01:03:23.340
I, not a fan.

1492
01:03:23.340 --> 01:03:26.790
I think it usually causes a lot more difficulties

1493
01:03:26.790 --> 01:03:28.860
with your relationship with the patient.

1494
01:03:28.860 --> 01:03:32.520
They're beautifully produced little packets

1495
01:03:32.520 --> 01:03:34.170
that the patient gets, you know, red, white,

1496
01:03:34.170 --> 01:03:36.120
and blue for the different medications.

1497
01:03:37.860 --> 01:03:39.780
And really what that tells you is that

1498
01:03:39.780 --> 01:03:41.730
who a patient may be at increased risk

1499
01:03:41.730 --> 01:03:42.930
for a certain antidepressant.

1500
01:03:42.930 --> 01:03:45.900
It does not imply that the patient may benefit from it.

1501
01:03:45.900 --> 01:03:49.710
We've known who's at risk for certain things for decades

1502
01:03:49.710 --> 01:03:51.810
and we haven't needed genetic test to tell us.

1503
01:03:51.810 --> 01:03:56.810
And the studies are really terrible about its efficacy

1504
01:03:56.910 --> 01:03:58.020
from a cost savings

1505
01:03:58.020 --> 01:03:59.100
and from a quality of life,

1506
01:03:59.100 --> 01:04:00.840
much less from an efficacy standpoint

1507
01:04:00.840 --> 01:04:02.220
for depression and anxiety.

1508
01:04:02.220 --> 01:04:04.830
So I tend to avoid them.

1509
01:04:04.830 --> 01:04:06.240
If I do prescribe them,

1510
01:04:06.240 --> 01:04:08.190
that's with a very distinct reason that I'm going

1511
01:04:08.190 --> 01:04:11.226
to change my therapy as a result of them.

1512
01:04:11.226 --> 01:04:13.620
Otherwise I don't get them.

1513
01:04:13.620 --> 01:04:16.563
<v ->And with that, please join me in thanking Dr. Heinrich.</v>

